      "id":"music/2013/oct/17/empirical-jazz-benyounes-quartet-review",
      "sectionId":"music",
      "sectionName":"Music",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T11:14:46Z",
      "webTitle":"Empirical/Benyounes Quartet – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/oct/17/empirical-jazz-benyounes-quartet-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/2013/oct/17/empirical-jazz-benyounes-quartet-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"37",
        "trailText":"<p>Empirical's blend of contemporary jazz and classical, backed up by a string quartet, was uneven but always engaging, writes <strong>John Fordham</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Empirical/Benyounes Quartet – review",
        "body":"<p>Stravinsky's contention that music is \"by its very nature, essentially powerless to express anything at all\" – that it's simply, but extraordinarily, a speculation in sound and time – seems to bypass <a href=\"http://www.empiricalmusic.com/\" title=\"\">Empirical</a>. In six packed years the British group have evolved from a contemporary jazz outfit to their present incarnation as a jazz/classical chamber ensemble. The band's 2008 debut album had such sassy titles as Fat Cat and Dark Lady, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/aug/22/empirical-tabula-rasa-review\" title=\"\">their latest</a> looms with weighty tracks – The Simple Light Shines Brightest, Cosmos, or The Prophet. But if Empirical, augmented here by the classical <a href=\"http://www.benyounesquartet.com/\" title=\"\">Benyounes Quartet</a>, sound at odds with Stravinsky's pragmatism, they nonetheless did plenty of fascinating speculating in sound and time in this gig, even if (as on the new album) they could have clipped a spare moment here and there.</p><p><a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/empiricalmusic/cosmos\">Reading on mobile? Listen to the track here</a></p><p>The core quartet – saxophonist Nathaniel Facey, vibraphonist Lewis Wright, bassist Tom Farmer and drummer Shane Forbes – opened with Facey's soulfully plaintive long-note weave over a bass vamp (Yin and Yang) and Wright's punchily percussive stop-start theme, Bellsonian Scales. The Benyounes joined for Facey's The Simple Light Shines Brightest, in which a jazzily twisting, drums-shadowed strings melody gave way to a seductive daydream, a fast bebop vibes solo, and a typically composer-like alto sax break from the composer, always attentive to the ways in and out of even the shortest phrase. This thoughtful and sophisticated performer even sounded more like a french hornist than a saxophonist amid the mists of the Benyounes' floating opening to Tom Farmer's Ascent and Descent.</p><p>Wright's The Prophet brought a rootsier, folk-melodic feel to the music, and the jazz group's free-flow reached a new heat, invoking the classic <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2010/aug/09/john-coltrane-giant-step\" title=\"\">Coltrane quartet's tumultuous collective roar</a> early in the second half. In contrast, they came closer to <a href=\"http://www.porticoquartet.com/\" title=\"\">Portico Quartet</a> on Farmer's chiming The Healer, powered up their jazz engine again for the whippy Empiricism – and steered Lewis Wright at his most delicate into the swirling, deep-toned strings lines on Forbes' Repentance, the most memorably transporting genre-blend of an uneven but engaging night.</p><p>• Did you catch this show – or any other recently? Tell us about it using #gdnreview</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420232399|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|b9a7d1dfb366fd5062a479779db9f5671b2802c1 -->",
