      "id":"music/musicblog/2013/oct/17/opera-naked-lynn-binstock",
      "sectionId":"music",
      "sectionName":"Music",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T10:18:12Z",
      "webTitle":"Opera: the bare essentials",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2013/oct/17/opera-naked-lynn-binstock",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/music/musicblog/2013/oct/17/opera-naked-lynn-binstock",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>Stripping opera down can bring new life – and new audiences – to the form, writes Opera Naked creator <strong>Lynn Binstock</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Opera: the bare essentials",
        "body":"<p>\"Sumptuous, extravagant and empty\" was one reviewer's take on a <a href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/37d33f68-04cd-11e3-9e71-00144feab7de.html#axzz2hPdNliVq\" title=\"\">Salzburg festival opera production this summer</a>.</p><p>Money can corrupt anyone and anything. But is opera especially prone to such corruption because of the perceived need to present a grand spectacle? Some people would say that the reviewer's dictum above charactises all opera.</p><p>Opera draws on many means to move our hearts, engage our minds and stimulate our senses. Such an experience doesn't come cheap. The main cost is people: a conventional production requires a cast of soloists boosted by a large orchestra, chorus and often dancers. Another small army – from the creative and music teams to the backstage staff – builds and looks after the show.</p><p>Whether it's endowing ancient myths with the latest technical wizardry (as in the Metropolitan Opera's recent Ring cycle) or reproducing historically informed splendours, opera productions can cost hundreds of thousands of pounds. And even with princely patrons it needs grand theatres to stand a chance of recouping costs through ticket sales. The pressure to present a spectacle is understandable.</p><p>But money cannot guarantee a great performance or production. And although access to opera has often been the preserve of those with wealth and education, it has also been – and still is – loved passionately by many without either. Even stripped down, opera can be incredibly powerful, especially in spaces smaller than your average opera house.</p><p>Small-scale opera comes in all shapes, sizes and standards: in <a href=\"http://kingsheadtheatre.com/operaupclose.html\" title=\"\">pubs</a>, <a href=\"http://www.silentopera.co.uk/\" title=\"\">factories</a> and <a href=\"http://www.gardenopera.co.uk/\" title=\"\">gardens</a>. For a glimpse, check out what the <a href=\"http://www.theoperagroup.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Opera Group</a>, <a href=\"http://www.sizezeroopera.com/\" title=\"\">Size Zero Opera</a>, <a href=\"http://www.tete-a-tete.org.uk/\">Tête à Tête</a>, <a href=\"http://www.hgo.org.uk/\" title=\"\">Hampstead Garden Opera</a> or <a href=\"http://fulhamopera.com/site/\" title=\"\">Fulham Opera</a> are up to.</p><p>Of course, limiting or doing without an orchestra and a chorus – two of opera's greatest glories – is the worst privation faced by small companies. But reducing costs by performing in small or unusual venues, hiring up-and-coming singers and building simple sets can definitely make opera more accessible and less intimidating for those who have never ventured inside the Royal Opera House or Coliseum. And it can make it more fun for those who have. A certain amount of \"poor opera\" may even be a healthy corrective to purify and revive the form.</p><p>Opera speaks very effectively for itself when you focus on what is essential: the singers who share the music, poetry, characters, and story with us. Peter Brook did this brilliantly with <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PhINJ5RTG5k\" title=\"\">his famous adaptation of Carmen</a>, an 82-minute show featuring four singers, three actors, a 15-piece orchestra and very little set. It ran for 150 performances in its first season in Paris and then toured the world.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420240944'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Music/Pix/pictures/2013/10/16/1381935845488/Opera-Naked-ST-James-stud-008.jpg' alt='Opera Naked, ST James studio theatre, oct 2013' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>'Operatic cabaret' … Opera Naked includes including arias from Madama Butterfly, Tosca and Tannhäuser. Photograph: Robert Workman</figcaption></figure><p>Five years ago I set up <a href=\"http://www.unexpectedopera.com/\">Unexpected Opera</a> to challenge expectations of what opera is and to share it with new audiences in productions such as Barber of Savile Row, Orpheus Down Under and a staged Messiah (which brought operatic performances to community choral singers). This week, we're taking our new show, <a href=\"http://www.stjamestheatre.co.uk/events/opera-naked/\">Opera Naked</a>, to London's intimate St James Studio.</p><p>Opera Naked came about partly as a reaction to programmes like Pop Star to Opera Star and to the \"opera stars\" who use microphones and have never performed a full role onstage. But it is, first of all, my love letter to singers and to the form itself.</p><p>The show features a series of dramatic vignettes about what singing opera involves, based on interviews with dozens of singers. We also include a selection of excerpts, chosen because they are special to us, or because they bring to life central aspects of what opera even without sets or scenery. Favourites come from Carmen, Madam Butterfly, I Pagliacci, Tosca and Onegin. </p><p>Then there's the \"Awful Auditions\" section, which, ok, might be a little bit exaggerated for fun, but faithfully represents reality. The cast tell us why they wanted to sing opera, and how they came to it. Opera singers aren't necessarily posh – Nadine Mortimer Smith, from Brixton, discovered opera after a career on the trading floor. Philip Spendley started out as a zookeeper and was a bank manager before he got the opera bug.</p><p>In our pilot performances last year you could feel the audience responding to the intense emotions and sensual impact, unhindered by pretence, snobbery or meaningless extravagance. With singers and little else, even \"bleeding chunks\" of opera can be overwhelming and gripping when they are performed by artists possessed of hard-won skills.</p><p>In a recent interview on <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b037pcv8/HARDtalk_Thomas_Hampson_Opera_Singer/\" title=\"\">HARDtalk with the baritone Thomas Hampson</a>, Sarah Montague voiced the usual complaints about opera's supposed elitism and inaccessibility, <a href=\"http://www.artsjournal.com/slippeddisc/2013/07/bbc-today-presenter-opera-is-one-of-the-least-watched-art-forms-in-the-world.html\" title=\"\">to the outrage of opera fans</a>. I wish <a href=\"http://www.scribd.com/doc/157406285/Letter-to-the-BBC?fb_action_ids=10151572401031947&amp;fb_action_types=og.likes&amp;fb_source=other_multiline&amp;action_object_map=%7B%2210151572401031947%22%3A458930794204883%7D&amp;action_type_map=%7B%2210151572401031947%22%3A%22og.likes%22%7D&amp;action_ref_map=%5B%5D\" title=\"\">the responses from some of these opera lovers</a> could be more widely exposed. I challenge those who agree with the position she presented to come to shows like those of Opera Naked and see if it changes their minds.</p><p>Opera is an expensive art form, but it is so rich in content that it can be incredibly powerful in its essential, \"naked\" form, without huge expenditure. The glamour and spectacle that opera often trades in can be hugely enjoyable and even help illuminate the work, but it isn't what opera is about. The theatre is in the voices. You can do without scenery and costumes, and even without the orchestra, but without singers it isn't opera.</p><p><em>Opera Naked is at </em><a href=\"http://www.stjamestheatre.co.uk\" title=\"\"><em>St James theatre </em></a><em>until 20 October 2013. Box office: 0844 264 2140. Find out more at: </em><a href=\"http://www.unexpectedopera.com\" title=\"\"><em>unexpectedopera.com</em></a><em> </em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420161596|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|357c65888cbde403947fc3a0cdf08f266a61dd9e -->",
