        "trailText":"<p>They're being called the Sex Pistols of Scottish folk, which is generous. A Clashy Mumfords, maybe</p>",
        "headline":"Washington Irving (New band of the day No 1,620)",
        "body":"<p><strong>Hometown</strong>: Oban, Scotland.   <br />      <br /><strong>The lineup</strong>: Joseph Black, Martin Anfield, Rory MacDonald, Kieran Heather and Chris McGarry.  </p><p><strong>The background</strong>: Yesterday, the Quietus posted <a href=\"http://thequietus.com/articles/13597-simon-price-critic-will-self\">an excellent article by Simon Price</a> (and the to-and-fro between the site's editor and a reader in the comments section was even more riveting), arguing for the \"parasitic but necessary\" role of the critic in the internet age. Price argued for the continued benefits of analysis and contextualisation, although he didn't talk about the other unexpected task that is often regarded as the remit of the critic: that of prophesier of the future. One of the unwritten roles of the music critic especially is that of A&amp;R person, the tacit acknowledgement being that we should be able to predict the fortunes or otherwise of a new act at will. </p><p>We mention this because in April 2008 we wrote about Mumford &amp; Sons <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/apr/14/popandrock3\">in this column</a>, and although we said something that we still stand by – they \"sound like Coldplay reincarnated as hillbillies\" – we are ashamed to say that at no point did we foresee that they would become one of the biggest bands on the planet. Today's new band are a bit Mumfords – albeit a more aggressive Mumfords, a Clashy Mumfords rather than a Coldplay one, which maybe means they're more <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8zVmx709Nrg\">the Men They Couldn't Hang</a> than M&amp;S – but again, we have no idea whether their rambunctious form of folk will catch on beyond the indie-gig milieu in which they currently operate in their native Scotland and beyond. </p><p> <a href=\"https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Fplaylists%2F12235944\">Reading on mobile? Click here to listen</a></p><p>Much is being made of that rambunctiousness. \"They're carrying the folk torch and using it as an arsonist might,\" their tourmates Frightened Rabbit have teased, while their press release declares their intention to \"revolutionise folk music in their own unique way\" and early reviews have hailed \"a band hell-bent of injecting a dose of rock'n'roll into the folk scene\",  detecting in their \"visceral\" attack \"whiffs of Sex Pistols' Anarchy in the UK\". Wrote one website: \"They are more akin to Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds than they are their folk-leaning contemporaries.\" Equal fuss is made of their apparently pioneering divination of the darkness within folk, as they draw on the \"twisted tales of love, death and madness in traditional folk\" and give such contorted trad arr fol-de-rol some sonic welly. </p><p>Well, we can't hear such radical invention any more than we can estimate their commercial potential, and we could have sworn indie bands had been exploring folk's dark side for years. What Washington Irving do doesn't sound remotely new to our ears, attuned as they are to years of exposure to the Pogues and the aforementioned TMTCH. But certainly if you liked those groups you will probably be favourably disposed towards this lot. On Palomides, a track from their debut double-album – and we applaud their ambition in that regard – they sing in unison to denote comradeship and community spirit. The music is designed to rouse rabbles, or at least, crowds of students. You've Seen the Last of Me has the plangency, chime and melody of a Smiths song, almost, and proves how close Smiths songs were to folk, at times. You can just imagine Moz in a woolly sweater, yodelling along with this one. She Moved Through the Fair takes the original ballad and gives it extra contemporary wallop. Old St Luan is typical of their output: loud, strummy, with plenty of bash and crash. We really do want to conclude that they are a tougher Mumfords, but we haven't listened to the latter in five years, not even once, although if Washington Irving do make it big, fully expect us to take all the credit. </p><p><strong>The buzz</strong>: <a href=\"http://www.supajam.com/news/story/Washington-Irving-are-releasing-a-double-album\">\"Washington Irving are an indie folk act, but don't panic because they're still interesting.\" </a> <br />  <br /><strong>The truth</strong>: They're a Clashy Mumfords.      <br /> <br /><strong>Most likely to</strong>: Cover <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yPA_XuxUx3M\">Rainy Night in Soho</a>.</p><p><strong>Least likely to</strong>: Cover <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5DmIFIkcU7U\">Rainy Night in Georgia</a>.  </p><p><strong>What to buy</strong>: Palomides: Volumes I &amp; II is released by Instinctive Raccoon on November 4. </p><p><strong>File next to</strong>: Admiral Fallow, Skinny Lister, Dry the River, Men They Couldn't Hang.    </p><p><strong>Links</strong>: <a href=\"http://washingtonirving.bandcamp.com\">washingtonirving.bandcamp.com</a>.  </p><p><strong>Friday's new band</strong>: Wilkinson.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420141381|2013-10-17T12:53:00Z|28a508c295324305a445f1cec46239a70baf1087 -->",
